Yeah, that's kinda the reason I-77 came to be, I wanted to expand upon it, and I had written around three pages in work of build up, of his goodbye kiss and what would become an empty promise following it. I had gotten to the point where he was gradually realizing he was living on borrowed time.
I scraped it entirely, because I felt I was borrowing too much from "All Quiet on the Western Front" for the war which I wanted to leave vague in the first half of the 20th century.
So now I'm reading some war autobiographies for research.
As for how this relates to I-77 I felt it was ill fitting seeing as Ms. Serval recently happened and I didn't want to jump on the tragedy bandwagon. I also wanted to write a war story kinda based on the Troubles in Northern Ireland (yes I am aware war is a central theme in all of my storied for day one but goddammit I base half this shit of D&D worlds I build). The Waifur(s) requirements were
A). Unexpected
B). Very Hateable
C). Local to West Virginia
So after three hours and listening to Thirteenth step by APC one too many times I came up with the world building and "most" of the first update

Dude, an amazing ending is a perfect tool for a writer to write the rest of the story.
Basically you pick an action your central hero does that affects others in your ending, i.e. apologizes for being xyz
Then you come up with their weaknesses off this. Write a scene based off this.
Then their desire, what they're after in the story. Write a scene cleverly showing this
Then their opponents, people after the same thing as the hero or just wanting to stop the hero. Once again base a scene introducing them.
Then, the plan. How they are going to deal with their opponants and achieve their desire.
Then if your endings that well thought out the Final battle and the new equilibrium are already written out.
Then just write plot scenes inbetween or I can give you the pdf of anatomy of the story to see a more detailed execution of this.
